,"nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gibbs","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the common medieval personal name <i>Gibb</i> (see   Gibb  ), a pet form of   Gilbert  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Gibb","meanings":["English: from the personal name <i>Gibb</i>, a pet form of <i>Gilbert</i> (compare   Gibbs  ). This surname is also frequent in Scotland."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Fenworth","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Hanworth   or   Hainsworth  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hainsworth","meanings":["English:","(Yorkshire): habitational name from Hainworth in Keighley, Yorkshire, named from the Old English personal name <i>Hagena</i> + Old English <i>worth</i> ‘enclosure’. The intrusive <i>-s-</i> was acquired by the late 15th century, probably through false association with the Lancashire surname <i>Ainsworth</i> in 2 below.","variant of   Ainsworth   in Lancashire. Names such as <i>de Haynesworth</i> and <i>de Heynesworth</i> occur in the surrounding area in the 14th century."]},{"name":"Hanworth","meanings":["English: locative name from Cold Hanworth or Potter Hanworth (both Lincs) or Hanworth (Norfolk). The early bearers can be difficult to distinguish from those for   Hainsworth  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":5,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When William Fenworth Gibbs was born in 1450, in Somerset, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert Gibbs, was 22 and his mother, Elizabeth Fenworth Lady, was 20. He had at least 1 daughter with Lady Elizabeth Yarde. He died in 1483, in Somerset, England, at the age of 33."},"et":{"1450–1483":"1450–1483","1450–1500":"1450–1500","1481–1539":"1481–1539","1428–Male":"1428–Surnud","1430–1470":"1430–1470","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1430":"1430","1450":"1450","1483":"1483","1470":"1470","1481":"1481","1539":"1539","1428":"1428","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Buckland Dinham, Somerset, England":"Buckland Dinham, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1450–1483":"1450–1483","1450–1500":"1450–1500","1481–1539":"1481–1539","1428–Male":"1428–Kuollut","1430–1470":"1430–1470","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1430":"1430","1450":"1450","1483":"1483","1470":"1470","1481":"1481","1539":"1539","1428":"1428","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Buckland Dinham, Somerset, England":"Buckland Dinham, Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lancashire, Engla